p.
  Buttons are displayed inline-block, so in order to preserve
  vertical rhythm, be sure to contain them in typographical block-level elements
  such as paragraphs or lists.
p.
  Button Components may be in the form of #[code.docs-code a] elements (links or anchors) or
  #[code.docs-code button] elements.
  Keep in mind these button usage guidelines: #[code.docs-code button]s should
  indicate action and be worded actionably. Use an #[code.docs-code a] instead of a #[code.docs-code button]
  if there is a
  meaningful target href or url. Of course, #[code.docs-code a] elements
  as well as #[code.docs-code button] elements may be styled
  to look like Button Components.
p Every Button Component must have styles available for each of the following states:
dl
  dt.-fw-7 default
  dd the button does something or the link goes somewhere, but the user is not interacting with the component
  dt.-fw-7 hover/focus
  dd the user&rsquo;s cursor is hovering over the component, or the user agent is focusing on the component
  dt.-fw-7 active
  dd the user is in the process of clicking/activating the component
  dt.-fw-7 disabled
  dd
    | the component is inaccessable and/or does nothing, and the user
    |  may not interact with it.
    |  this state is implemented by
    ul
      li a #[code.docs-code button] with the #[code.docs-code disabled] attribute, or
      li.
        an #[code.docs-code a] with the #[code.docs-code href] attribute #[em absent]
        (this is not the same as an empty attribute #[code.docs-code [href=""]]).
p.
  Each of these states is demonstrated in the sections below, however
  only the code for the default state is shown.
